    <node id="Generalized Linear Models">
      <data key="d0">Generalized Linear Models</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Generalized linear models represent a broad class of models that generalize traditional linear models to accommodate various types of response variables.&lt;SEP&gt;Generalized Linear Models are a flexible generalization of ordinary least squares regression, encompassing logistic regression among other forms.&lt;SEP&gt;Generalized Linear Models are statistical models used for modeling outcomes which can take on multiple values, including logistic regression.&lt;SEP&gt;Generalized Linear Models are a framework for modeling response variables through linear combinations of explanatory variables, used in conjunction with softmax regression.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-023cc775f8b1adeebc9c45d2e9f6fe90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-674af09a64beddbff4e4e4b6e543709a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38d7cccd02d2282bbd339ef51ba43f85&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1aa4c1f1bcccecc7faef4f12ad096763</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1767942407</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Logistic Regression">
      <data key="d0">Logistic Regression</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Logistic regression is a statistical method used for binary classification problems where outcomes are typically 0 or 1.&lt;SEP&gt;Logistic Regression is a statistical method for binary classification, which models the probability of a binary outcome using a logistic function.&lt;SEP&gt;Logistic Regression is a modeling technique mentioned in the text that benefits from the application of algorithms like Newton’s Method.&lt;SEP&gt;Logistic Regression is a statistical method for predicting binary outcomes based on one or more predictor variables.&lt;SEP&gt;Logistic Regression is a statistical method used for binary classification problems, modeling the probability of outcomes based on predictor variables.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-023cc775f8b1adeebc9c45d2e9f6fe90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7d9737bbcc99dd55bb4b79cf055977a2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38d7cccd02d2282bbd339ef51ba43f85&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1aa4c1f1bcccecc7faef4f12ad096763&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d65cfad802d1335db113217e2cb6afbe</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1767942407</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Gaussian Distribution">
      <data key="d0">Gaussian Distribution</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The Gaussian distribution, also known as the normal distribution, is a continuous probability distribution characterized by its bell-shaped curve, defined by its mean and variance.&lt;SEP&gt;Gaussian Distribution is a statistical distribution characterized by its bell-shaped curve, often used to model real-valued random variables.&lt;SEP&gt;The Gaussian Distribution is a statistical distribution that is frequently referenced in the lecture and is related to normal distributions and the exponential family.&lt;SEP&gt;The Gaussian Distribution, also known as the normal distribution, is a continuous probability distribution that is symmetric about the mean.&lt;SEP&gt;Gaussian Distribution refers to a continuous probability distribution characterized by a symmetric bell-shaped curve.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-023cc775f8b1adeebc9c45d2e9f6fe90&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1dcfa4fdc2012c4e3a3c336e39e4afec&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-486f08627d119b0879789e4cf88e8904&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38d7cccd02d2282bbd339ef51ba43f85&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1aa4c1f1bcccecc7faef4f12ad096763</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1767942407</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="K Possible Outcomes">
      <data key="d0">K Possible Outcomes</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">K Possible Outcomes refer to scenarios where predictions can involve more than two outcomes in a classification problem.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-023cc775f8b1adeebc9c45d2e9f6fe90</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1767942407</data>
      <data key="d6" />
